snippet.textDisplay:
“Khara” (salt) is life, but in their tradition and songs, they often call it “meetha” (sweet) because it sustains families and generations, even though the work is extremely harsh.

The Agariyas spend 8–9 months in the blazing desert sun, pumping brine from underground and letting it crystallize into salt.

Their lives are tough—away from cities, with very little access to health, schools, or modern facilities—but their pride in creating the “white gold” of India makes the story deeply emotional.

A song that captures this contrast—hardship vs. sweetness, pain vs. pride—can easily give goosebumps.
